  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Proprioceptive weighting changes may explain differences in postural control performance. In
      addition, the respiratory movement has a disturbing effect on postural balance. Postural
      balance seems to be impaired in individuals with respiratory disorders. Besides the essential
      role of respiration, the diaphragm may also play an important role in the control of the
      trunk and postural balance. Deficits in proprioception are found in a subgroup of patients
      with low back pain. In addition, disorders of respiration have been identified as strongly
      related to low back pain.

      The aim of the study is to clarify whether inspiratory muscle training has a positive effect
      on proprioceptive postural control in individuals with recurrent low back pain.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
